The line graph compares the number of shop openings and closures in one country, for a period starting from 2011 until 2018.

Overall, both the openings and closures displayed a roughly downward trend over the whole period shown. Also, for most years (6 out of 8), there were more shops closed than new shops opened.

In 2011, 8500 shops started business, a figure never surpassed later in the period. The number dropped sharply next year, to about 4000, before it climbed up steadily for the next 2 years, arriving at a local peak of a little over 6000 in 2014. After that, the number of new shops was generally downhill, decreasing to 4000 in 2015 and stayed there without much change for the next 2 years, then down again to 3000 in 2018, the end of the period.

As for the closures, about 6400 shops closed down in 2011, well below the number of new shops in the same year. The closures stayed in the 6000-7000 range for the next 3 years with some variation. The most dramatic change happened in 2015, when as few as 600 stores went out of business, a mere fraction of the new openings. This number rebounded quickly in the next year to 5000 and stayed there throughout the rest of the period. 
